It has often struck me that his genius is akin to that of Milton. He displays a wonderful depth and fervour of thought, expressed in language of singular force and beauty; an admirable faculty of clear and vigorous and well-sustained philosophical reasoning; and a style equa] in its purity and correctness to that of Terence, Caesar or Cicero, and superior to that of any writer of the Augustan agel!
